column1: Will China conduct bilateral military exercises with either Iran or Saudi Arabia before 1 October 2016?
column5: ['Yes, with only Iran', 'Yes, with both', 'Yes, with only Saudi Arabia', 'No']
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict']
column11: This question was closed on option D ('No') with a closing date of 30 September 2016. Bilateral military exercises could include field exercises involving naval, air, or ground forces. Table-top exercises, war games, or simulations would not suffice to resolve the question. Increasing tension between Iran and Saudi Arabia have complicated diplomatic efforts for Beijing, which is seeking to tighten diplomatic and military ties with both nations (World Politics Review, CNBC, The Diplomat). Recommended Questions Will Iran's President Hassan Rouhani meet Saudi Arabia's King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud before 1 September 2016? Will Russia conduct a naval exercise in the Western Hemisphere with a Central or South American country before 1 July 2016? Will Bahrain, Qatar, or the UAE return an ambassador to Iran before 18 October 2016?

Like so many other questions, I regret getting into this one after I've had a day or so to more fully contemplate the structure and details. On this one I don't foresee any more difficulty than I've grown accustomed to with GJ questions. I do, however, feel the structure of this question is not as good as it could be. The Yes categories should be structured as conditionals. It's quite enough, I think, to forecast upon the yes/no outcome in itself. In comparison, the varieties of "yes," while not trivial amongst themselves, are trivial in comparison to the "yes/no" outcome. There would seem to be a qualitative difference between a forecast that is wrong on the yes/no step, as compared to a forecast that is wrong on the specific yes outcome.

This is my initial forecast on the question. The only country that can prevent Syria and the entire near Middle East from falling under Western (w/ Russian collaboration) control is China. China needs to make a move or it will be primarily reliant upon energy resources from only two Middle Eastern sources: Iran or a Western dominated coalition that includes Russia. It is in the interest of China to keep the remaining Middle Eastern countries as independent as possible, and while China could conceivably move directly into Syria in support of Assad, a more likely initial step would be to demonstrate, via joint exercises, that China is prepared to defend their access to "non-dominated" Middle Eastern energy resources.
I am forecasting based on the general news reports and GJP consensus.

Yale Global Online, July 7, 'China Pivots to the Middle East and Iran - China rushes to invest in Iran, a Middle East pivot, as the US stubbornly sticks to sanctions': http://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/china-pivots-middle-east-and-iran Clips from YGO article: 'China’s interest in Iran goes beyond its energy resources. It has keen interest in Iran’s geostrategic location, bordering both the Caspian Sea and the Persian Gulf. The location enables China carry out the One Belt One Road agenda. Iran stands as China’s most important ally in the Persian Gulf, and China may find it difficult to deepen cooperation with Gulf Cooperation Council countries, given their positive ties with the United States. Iran on the other hand, due to historic ties with China and longstanding suspicion of the United States, remains a trustworthy ally for China. As noted by analyst Jeffry S Payne, “the overland Silk Road cannot effectively connect the east to the west without Iran as an integrated part.” China conducted joint naval exercises with Iran in 2014, and this may be a way to keep a check on growing naval cooperation between India and Iran – two countries that conducted joint naval exercises in 2003, 2006 and 2015. Iran is also following in China’s footsteps to create an anti-US anti-access area denial strategy, or A2/AD, to reduce US military supremacy in the Persian Gulf and the Mediterranean Sea. China undoubtedly expects Tehran to play an integral part in Beijing’s string of pearls – building a string of naval facilities in the Arabian Sea and Indian Ocean to counter American influence. Middle East markets are essential for China’s One Belt One Road program of building a network of manufacturing and transportation centers in Central Asia and Europe. Beijing also looks beyond Iran – establishing nuclear cooperation with Saudi Arabia and in the process of building a relationship with other GCC countries. This could lead to reducing tensions between rivals Saudi Arabia and Iran by providing economic opportunities through the One Belt One Road initiative. This requires balance on the part of Beijing. In January, Xi traveled to the Middle East, visiting Riyadh as well as Tehran probably to assure both and discourage misinterpretations that China supports one country over the other.'

Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Hua Chunying stated that the Chinese support "peace talks between the Syrian government and the opposition under the auspices of the UN and the mediation efforts by Staffan de Mistura, UN Special Envoy for Syria. Peace talks serve as the only practical way out of the Syrian crisis, the outcome of which will be more sustainable compared with other alternatives. Peace talks, the process of which may be long and tortuous, need to be consistently pushed forward. We call on the two sides to advance the talks from easy to difficult in a step-by-step manner, proceed from issues where they share similar stances, gradually establish mutual trust, pool consensus, and build up momentum so as to find a political solution that accommodates the legitimate concerns of all parties. China will continue to work with relevant parties and contribute positively to the political settlement of the Syrian issue. As you said, Special Envoy of the Chinese government on the Syrian issue Xie Xiaoyan set off to Geneva on April 17. He will get in touch with parties to the peace talks from the UN, the Syrian government and the opposition, follow the progress of the negotiations and promote peace talks. Later, Special Envoy Xie Xiaoyan will also visit Syria, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Russia and have an in-depth exchange of views with all relevant parties on seeking a political settlement of the Syrian issue."

The Diplomat, April 15, 'Going Blue: The Transformation of China’s Navy - Chinese naval vessels are increasingly operating father and farther away from their home waters.': http://thediplomat.com/2016/04/going-blue-the-transformation-of-chinas-navy/ Clips from article: "This trend from brown to blue-water operations continued to mature over the next several decades and in May 2015, China issued a white paper entitled, China’s Military Strategy. The paper outlined the strategy of “active defense,” which is essentially an amalgamation of the concepts of offshore defense and open seas protection. The strategy maintains, “The traditional mentality that control of the land is more important than control of the sea must be abandoned, and great importance has to be attached to managing the seas and oceans and protecting maritime rights and interests.” The ideas articulated in this strategy have already begun to crystallize; China’s ships have progressively been operating away from their coasts over the years and they are going to continue to operate even further and for longer periods. However, in order to prove its mettle, China has to do more than just operate far from home; they must demonstrate significant operational capability. The Pentagon’s 2015 report on China’ s Military Power noted, “Whereas ‘near seas’ defense remains the PLA Navy’s primary focus, China’s gradual shift to the ‘far seas’ has necessitated that its Navy support operational tasks outside the first island chain with multi-mission, long-range, sustainable naval platforms with robust self-defense capabilities.” China has set out to do exactly that. Their naval fleet has provided an escort for over 6,000 commercial ships; their hospital ship Peace Ark has been frequently dispatched to provide healthcare to countries in need; and their warships are increasingly relied upon for real-world missions from counter-piracy to evacuations of Chinese citizens." See also @Gonzo , April 17 post, links and most excellent commentary. Changing my mix incrementally based on his analysis.

I can make either case here. It may be that China will think it a good idea to try to show that they can operate effectively beyond the immediate region, in which case joint exercises would be a Good Idea. Or it may be that China will think they needn't bother to stretch their forces any thinner, what with having plenty to do in the East and South China Seas. As for the first, now that piracy has slackened some in the Arabian Sea, there is less point to joint maneuvers there, and there is certainly no reason for either Iran or Saudi Arabia to paddle that far east. So my guess is that China's attitude just now is not to engage in needless exercises far afield from their current area of interest. The operative word is "guess."

In addition, China and Iran have a strategic partnership and will help each other through military exercise. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China%E2%80%93Saudi_Arabia_relations + https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China%E2%80%93Iran_relations China wants to become more involves in the middle east and believes that a conducive way to do that is by having a military exercise with Saudi Arabia: http://www.breitbart.com/national-security/2016/01/15/china-ramps-up-propaganda-not-a-stranger-in-middle-east/ Arguments in favor of a low probability: China does not do military exercises with countries far away from them: http://thediplomat.com/2016/01/chinas-marines-conduct-first-military-exercises-in-the-gobi-desert/ Iran and Saudi Arabia do not have a good relationship and will be unwilling to cooperate with each other: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran%E2%80%93Saudi_Arabia_relations Saudi Arabia launched the largest military exercise so far, but did not include the US nor big powers so would be unlikely to do a military exercise with China: https://www.rt.com/news/332454-saudi-arabia-big-drills/ China has already planned to do a military exercise with Russia during 2016 so it is unlikely that they will do another before the year is over: http://thediplomat.com/2015/06/russia-plans-south-china-sea-naval-exercise-with-china-in-2016/

At the moment, China is already busy with military exercises with Russia, while Saudi Arabia didn't include China in its last military exercises. Even though they are allies, there is a low chance China will have time to organize military exercises with either Iran or Saudi Arabia before October.

The chances China conducts bilateral military exercises with Iran or Saudi Arabia by October are quite low considering that China, Iran and Saudi Arabia are currently doing separate military exercises and it would take a lot of planning to do bilateral exercises. Also since China rarely does exercises with countries far away, it is unlikely they will conduct any exercises with Iran or Saudi Arabia by October. There is also very little chance they conduct exercises with both since Saudi Arabia and Iran do not get along well.
Passage of time, it seems an exercise is far less likely in the time left.

The strait of Hormuz is too important for China's trade and energy supplies to ignore, and China itself cannot maintain a fleet there to keep lanes open as would the US. China's trade with Europe will soon be directly through Iran (by sea and rail), and Iran's oil and gas are key to China's future energy security. Iran itself presents many new investment opportunities that China sorely needs to help compensate for its slowing economy. Xi's recent trip to Iran was evidence of such. But S.A. is still the dominant oil producer when it comes to supply and control over prices so China must balance relations and help to avoid a SA-Iran direct conflict. China doesn't want to create an even more tense situation and cause energy supplies from either Iran or S.A. to be disrupted or hampered enough to cause increased volatility in prices and supply. So that leaves me with two choices for China here: either don't have exercises with either, or have exercises with both-. Having exercises with both would serve the additional purpose of further integrating the PLAN into the strait of Hormuz/ Gulf shipping lanes security and further asserting China's role in the middle east as regional / global power who can serve as an alternative to the US. Establishing the new PLAN base in Djibouti was the first step in this process.
